author: @roar779
text: If you want to do this from outside the models directory, follow my comment on the previous video, then do these:  1) cd into where "training","data",etc. directories are.  2)Instead of python3 export_inference_graph.py \ (4:25), run this from that directory: python3 $OBJ_DET/export_inference_graph.py \    2) Instead of running object_detection_tutorial.ipynb from here (6:31), copy that file into your directory and run jupyter notebook from there.  3) In .ipynb file (6:58) change those two lines under "Object detection imports" to these:    from object_detection.utils import label_map_util    from object_detection.utils import visualization_utils as vis_util    This way utils will be imported from your installation of object_detection module (.egg file), not the object_detection folder in models directory.   4) (*Optional) change TEST_IMAGE_PATH line (8:28) to this so you wouldn't have to rename every test image in your test_images directory:  TEST_IMAGE_PATHS = [ os.path.join(PATH_TO_TEST_IMAGES_DIR, i) for i in os.listdir(PATH_TO_TEST_IMAGES_DIR)]

author: @joaopdias
text: There are a lot of people that are  facing the problem of misclassification of objects that it was previously was trained on. To fix this issue the configuration file, in this case ssd_mobilenet_v1_pet.config, there is a new variable that was not at the time, the "load_all_detection_checkpoint_vars" is true by default and must be set to false. This variable freezes the weights in the final layers, so it will learn new things without forgetting the ones it had already seen, that is why it detects other objects, and the classification is incorrect because the pbtxt file was modified to map the id of the object to the name you wrote.

author: @hrshovon
text: hello sentdex, Thanks for your awesome tutorial. Here are some things I noticed after some experiments. 1. If you have the tf_slim directory added to PYTHONPATH. you can basically run your code from anywhere so your object_detection directory stays clean. Just specify the full paths in config files. 2. The new version of object detection seems to have a bug where it would show error when running the export inference graph file.      https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/16268 this fixes it.  I have written a GUI for performing the whole training and exporting thing. If you want, please visit https://github.com/hrshovon/tf_sensei to download and use it. It's still rough around the edges and very early release so please let me me if you face any issues.

author: @roar779
text: If you want to do this from outside the models directory, follow my comment on the previous video, then do these:  1) cd into where "training","data",etc. directories are.  2)Instead of python3 export_inference_graph.py \ (4:25), run this from that directory: python3 $OBJ_DET/export_inference_graph.py \    2) Instead of running object_detection_tutorial.ipynb from here (6:31), copy that file into your directory and run jupyter notebook from there.  3) In .ipynb file (6:58) change those two lines under "Object detection imports" to these:    from object_detection.utils import label_map_util    from object_detection.utils import visualization_utils as vis_util    This way utils will be imported from your installation of object_detection module (.egg file), not the object_detection folder in models directory.   4) (*Optional) change TEST_IMAGE_PATH line (8:28) to this so you wouldn't have to rename every test image in your test_images directory:  TEST_IMAGE_PATHS = [ os.path.join(PATH_TO_TEST_IMAGES_DIR, i) for i in os.listdir(PATH_TO_TEST_IMAGES_DIR)]
